 century.","habitational name from Finmere, Oxfordshire (from Old English <i>fīna</i> ‘wood-pecker’ + <i>mere</i> ‘pool, lake’, meaning ‘pool frequented by wood-peckers’), or Fenemere (also known as Fennymere) in Baschurch, Shropshire (derived from Old English <i>fyne</i> ‘mould’ + <i>mere</i> ‘pool, lake’, meaning ‘mouldy lake’). Perhaps also from one or more of the following places in Buckinghamshire: Finemere Wood in Quainton, Fenemore's Farm in Oakley, and Finnamore Farm in Ibstone.","English:"]}]},{"name":"Philip","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Greek name <i>Philippos</i>, meaning ‘lover of horses’, from <i>philein</i> ‘to love’ + <i>hippos</i> ‘horse’. This was popular in the classical period and since. It was the name of the father of  Alexander the Great . It was also the name of one of Christ's apostles, of a deacon ordained by the apostles after the death of Christ, and of several other early saints.  See also  Philippa ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Philip Finamore was born about 1282, in Devon, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son with Philip Finamore."},"et":{"Abt 1282–":"umbes 1282–Surnud","1279–Male":"1279–Surnud","1300–Male":"1300–Surnud","1282–Female":"1282–Surnud","Abt 1282":"umbes 1282","1279":"1279","1300":"1300","1282":"1282","Fenne,Devon,Eng":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Of Fenne,Devon,Eng":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1282–":"noin 1282–Kuollut","1279–Male":"1279–Kuollut","1300–Male":"1300–Kuollut","1282–Female":"1282–Kuollut","Abt 1282":"noin 1282","1279":"1279","1300":"1300","1282":"1282","Fenne,Devon,Eng":"Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Of Fenne,Devon,Eng":"Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt 1282–":"environ 1282–Décédée","1279–Male":"1279–Décédé","1300–Male":"1300–Décédé","1282–Female":"1282–Décédée","Abt 1282":"environ 1282","1279":"1279","1300":"1300","1282":"1282"